<h1><a class="anchor" name="pageConfFiles">Configuration Files </a></h1>BioRadio device configurations (see section on Device Configuration) can be saved to and loaded from file.<h2><a class="anchor" name="confFilesFields">
Fields in the Configuration File</a></h2>
The configuration file is divided into two sections: <a class="el" href="pageconffiles.html#confFieldsSysSettings">System Settings</a>, for overarching settings, and <a class="el" href="pageconffiles.html#confFieldsDAQSettings">DAQ Board Settings</a>, for individual input configuration.<h3><a class="anchor" name="confFieldsSysSettings">
System Settings</a></h3>
Settings listed under the [System] section of the configuration file apply to all of the ten Fast Inputs (Ch1-Ch8, Airflow and DC Aux).<p>
<ul>
<li><b>SystemSampleRate</b> – The number of samples-per-second acquired on Fast Inputs. Should be 960, 800, 768, 600, 480, 384, 256, or 128. Slow Inputs will be sampled once every ten samples of Fast Inputs.</li></ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li><b>BitResolution</b> – The number of bits used in recording each sample on Fast Inputs. Should be 4, 8, 12, or 16.</li></ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li><b>SweepsPerPacket</b> – The number of sweeps over all enabled Fast Inputs included in one data packet. Should always be 10.</li></ul>
<h3><a class="anchor" name="confFieldsDAQSettings">
DAQ Board Settings</a></h3>
Settings listed under the [DAQ Board] section of the configuration file. Each input has a string of settings labeled as “Channel_XX” where XX is the channel number, beginning at 00 and continuing to 13, in the order: CH1-8, Airflow, DC Aux, Accelerometer, Body Position, Heart Rate, SpO2. Slow Inputs have fixed Range, Resolution, and Sample Rate, and therefore need only the “Enabled” state listed.<p>
<ul>
<li><b>InputName</b> – A name to be used for referring to an input; not stored in device hardware: exists in, and with a lifespan of, the BioRadio150 device object.</li></ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li><b>BitResolution</b> – The resolution, in bits, of samples recorded on an input. Only necessary for Fast Inputs, and should be equal to the BitResolution in System Settings. Slow Inputs have fixed resolutions.</li></ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li><b>Index</b> – Unused. Set to 0.</li></ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li><b>SampleRate</b> – The number of samples acquired per second on all Fast Inputs. Set to SystemSampleRate. Slow inputs are automatically sampled at 1/10th this rate.</li></ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li><b>UpperScale</b> – The value in Volts corresponding to the maximum ADC value that can be reported by the device on this channel. Allowed values are included in Table 1: Scaling. Fast Inputs only.</li></ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li><b>LowerScale</b> - The value in Volts corresponding to the minimum ADC value that can be reported by the device on this channel. Usually equal to UpperScale * -1.0. Allowed values are included in Table 1: Scaling. Fast Inputs only.</li></ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li><b>ADCUpper</b> – The base-10 value of the maximum ADC value that can be reported by the device on this channel. Normally, this will be 2BitResolution – 1. Fast Inputs only.</li></ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li><b>ADCLower</b> – The base-10 value of the minimum ADC value that can be reported by the device on this channel. Normally, this will be 0. Fast Inputs only.</li></ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li><b>Truncate</b> – Unused. Set to 0.</li></ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li><b>RangeIndex</b> – The index of the available input ranges by which the data on this channel should be scaled. See Table 1: Scaling. Fast Inputs only.</li></ul>
